body:
Crowley was a man of words, or as some people might say, a man who liked to hear himself speak. While, admittedly, he was known to drone on about this or that, sometimes at lengths that astonished even you, you found his actions and expressions far more telling than his words could ever be. A flit of his eyes, a slight shift in his jaw, a subtle change in posture, all things that most would miss or write off as nothing more than a mere character trait or impatience, but to you, you knew far better.

So when Crowley’s eyes met yours, holding your gaze as his tongue peaked out of his mouth and dragged slowly over his lower lip, you knew you’d gone too far.

Causing trouble was something you’d always been good at, but now that the King of Hell shared his throne with you, it had become more of a game than ever, one that said King of Hell was clearly growing weary of. Be that as it may, you had to fight to keep the grin from spreading across your face, going so far as to bite down on the inside of your cheeks as you begged them to remain neutral. Regardless of the fact that you had not a single regret for your actions, sometimes feigning your contrition was enough to save you from the brunt on your punishment.

“Dare I even ask?” Crowley drawled, bringing himself to stand before you as his chest rose and fell with a great sigh of exhaustion. It appeared as if he too were trying to control himself, though the emotion he was feeling was evidently rather different than your own.

Not trusting yourself to speak, you merely shrugged a shoulder, casting your gaze downwards and pulling your bottom lip between your teeth. You were far from innocent, but occasionally you could play the part rather convincingly when needed.

Unfortunately for you, as well as you knew Crowley, he knew you just as well, and he was having none of your act.

His pointer finger slipped delicately below your chin, caressing your jaw before tilting your face upwards to meet your gaze. You sucked in a sharp breath as the red began to swim and pool around in his eyes, marking just how cross he currently was, and indicating just how much trouble you were in for.

If you were being honest, there was a part of you that had wondered if you’d gone too far on this one… Even you had yet to push him to the point of having the red seep into his eyes, and it honestly thrilled you far more than it had any right to.

You heart hammered in your chest, it’s tune beating out anything but fear and Crowley’s face blanched for a moment before he composed himself and rolled his eyes incredulously.

“You can’t be serious?” he balked, narrowing his eyes slightly at you as squared his shoulders, seemingly uncertain as to whether or not to believe what you’d done, and far less willing to believe your reaction.

The smile you’d been fighting back could be contained no more and it drew across your lips as a final act of defiance, causing Crowley’s eyes to flair all the brighter and your heart to skip a beat. Closing the already small gap between you, his hand came to your face again, cupping your chin with perhaps a touch more force than necessary as he lowered his eyes to meet yours.

“Now, Darling… if you’d wanted some attention, I could think of a dozen other ways you could have gone about getting it,” Crowley mused, his anger abiding, but something more primal slipping into his tone.

You’d always been good as causing trouble, and when it came to Crowley, that was half the fun.

summary: tired: Anathema and Newt's relationship is unnecessary heterosexuality, forced into the plot of Good Omens in order to undermine...
body:
tired: Anathema and Newt’s relationship is unnecessary heterosexuality, forced into the plot of Good Omens in order to undermine the homosexual subtext between Aziraphale and Crowley

wired: Anathema and Newt’s relationship is a reflection, even an allegory, for heterosexuality into the media. The relationship is predicted, expected and even enforced - it happens because that is what happens. Meanwhile, Aziraphale and Crowley serve as a representation for homosexuality and queer representation in modern media. The relationship is forbidden, secret - and never mentioned even by the characters themselves

summary: Good Omens is one of my favourite books, it makes me laugh every time I re-read it and I wanted to make a comic for the serie's...
caption:
Good Omens is one of my favourite books, it makes me laugh every time I re-read it and I wanted to make a comic for the serie’s premiere! This is one of the silly bits I love from the book, I wonder if it’ll be on the show…

—

“Buenos Presagios” es uno de mis libros favoritos, me hace reír cada vez que lo re-leo y quería hacer un cómic aprovechando que se estrena la serie! Esta es una de las partes tontas del libro que me encantan, me pregunto si la incluirán en la serie…

summary: I have been waiting for a Good Omens TV adaptation since I first read the book over five years ago. I could not have imagined...
caption: I have been waiting for a Good Omens TV adaptation since I first read the book over five years ago. I could not have imagined something that looks so amazing. My favourite book with some of my favourite actors and characters. Could not have asked for a better end to my second year at uni. Thank you to everyone involved in its creation. This video is for my the best friends (maybe more) that is Aziraphale and Crowley.
